  "local_port": 53728,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do you clean a remote control?",
  "response": "Cleaning a remote control is a straightforward process, but it requires care to avoid damaging the device. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide:\n\n---\n\n### **What You\u2019ll Need:**\n- Isopropyl alcohol (70% or higher)\n- Microfiber cloth or soft lint-free cloth\n- Cotton swabs (optional)\n- Compressed air (optional)\n- Toothpick or soft brush (optional)\n\n---\n\n### **Steps to Clean a Remote Control:**\n\n1. **Remove the Batteries:**\n   - Open the battery compartment and remove the batteries to prevent damage or accidental activation.\n\n2. **Shake Out Loose Debris:**\n   - Gently shake the remote to dislodge any crumbs or dust.\n\n3. **Use Compressed Air (Optional):**\n   - If there\u2019s dirt or dust in hard-to-reach areas (e.g., around buttons), use compressed air to blow it out. Hold the can upright and spray in short bursts.\n\n4. **Wipe the Surface:**\n   - Dampen a microfiber cloth with a small amount of isopropyl alcohol (do not pour liquid directly on the remote). Wipe the entire surface to remove grime and fingerprints.\n\n5. **Clean Between Buttons:**\n   - Use a cotton swab lightly dampened with isopropyl alcohol to clean around and between the buttons. Be careful not to use too much liquid.\n\n6. **Remove Stubborn Dirt:**\n   - For stuck-on debris, use a toothpick or soft brush to gently remove it. Avoid scratching the surface.\n\n7. **Dry Thoroughly:**\n   - Allow the remote to air dry completely before reinserting the batteries.\n\n8. **Replace the Batteries:**\n   - Once the remote is dry, put the batteries back in and test it to ensure it works properly.\n\n---\n\n### **Tips:**\n- Avoid using water, household cleaners, or abrasive materials, as they can damage the remote.\n- Clean your remote regularly to prevent buildup of dirt and grime.\n\nBy following these steps, you can keep your remote control clean and functioning well!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
